s, protest songs, and hip-hop music; reproduced on manifestos and blogs; sent by email and text; scribbled on scraps of paper and posted on walls; performed publicly; and painted as graffiti. These forms of expression also resonated strongly with Spanish poets who had already been exploring the possibilities of ethical engagement and aesthetic creation. Poetry and Crisis explores how this essentially poetic sensibility emerged from tragedy, laying the groundwork for similar kinds of affective and grassroots mobilization that continue to grow in Europe today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMadrid Train Bombings, Madrid, Spain, 2004xSocial aspects. 0aMadrid Train Bombings, Madrid, Spain, 2004. 0aPoetryxSocial aspectszSpainzMadrid. 0aPoetryxTherapeutic use. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  a11-M.  a9/11.  aMadrid.  aPoetry.  aaffect.  acrisis.  acultural politics.  agraffiti.  agrassroots.  ahip hop.  aimmigrant.  amemorials.  amemory and memorialization.  amonuments.  aneoliberalism.  aperformance.  apost-Franco.  aterrorism.  atrauma.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP Single-User eBook-Package 2020z978311070827108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753078540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487530785423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487530785.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070827-1  UTP Single-User eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles